{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586946"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:40:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:40:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15109"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15109"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7797"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67918"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7797"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15109"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53383"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19018"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19021"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67918"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA histological section of renal cortex from a patient with benign nephrosclerosis shows arteriolar thickening and sclerotic glomeruli.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following additional histological features is most characteristic of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intratubular red blood cell casts","Intratubular granular casts","Intratubular epithelial casts","Intratubular hyaline casts","Intratubular fatty casts"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBenign nephrosclerosis is a condition associated with chronic hypertension that leads to arteriolar thickening, glomerular sclerosis, and tubular changes. A characteristic finding is the presence of \u003Cstrong\u003Eintratubular hyaline casts\u003C/strong\u003E, which are composed of Tamm-Horsfall protein and filtered proteins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other types of casts indicate different pathological processes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntratubular red blood cell casts\u003C/strong\u003E suggest glomerular bleeding and are typically seen in glomerulonephritis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntratubular granular casts\u003C/strong\u003E represent degraded cellular material and are non-specific findings\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntratubular epithelial casts\u003C/strong\u003E indicate acute tubular injury with sloughing of tubular epithelial cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntratubular fatty casts\u003C/strong\u003E are associated with heavy proteinuria as seen in nephrotic syndrome\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of arteriolar thickening, glomerular sclerosis, and hyaline casts is characteristic of chronic hypertensive damage to the kidney.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Benign nephrosclerosis is characterised by arteriolar thickening, glomerular sclerosis and hyaline casts due to chronic hypertension.","Hyaline casts are composed of Tamm-Horsfall protein and filtered proteins in the tubules.","Different types of casts indicate specific pathological processes - red cell casts suggest bleeding, epithelial casts indicate tubular injury, and fatty casts occur with heavy proteinuria."],"references":["Takebayashi S, Kiyoshi Y, Hisano S, Uesugi N, Sasatomi Y, Meng J, Sakata N. Benign nephrosclerosis: incidence, morphology and prognosis. Clin Nephrol. 2001 May;55(5):349-56. PMID: 11393379.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53383"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15109"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53383"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T20:44:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T20:44:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7797"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67918"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name